Module 27 – Deflection and Denial — The Bureaucratic Reflex 🛑📑

Core Message

Bureaucracies, including courts, often default to deflection rather than engagement.

⸻

Lesson Introduction

Understanding this reflex lets you prepare counter-responses that keep your case moving.

⸻

Teaching Block

1. Expect the Script
	•	“We don’t have jurisdiction,” “It’s too late,” “It’s too early.”

2. Have Counter-Responses Ready
	•	Show jurisdiction statutes, timeliness, or procedural exceptions.

3. Keep It in the Record
	•	Every counter-response should be filed, not just emailed.

⸻

Real-World Illustration

When told “your appeal is not the proper vehicle,” filing a procedural map demonstrated it was.

⸻

Assignment Prompt

Task:
List three common deflection statements and your counter.

⸻

Model Answer (Sample)
	1.	“We lack jurisdiction” → Cite statute granting jurisdiction.
	2.	“Too late” → Show tolling rules.
	3.	“Too early” → Show ripeness doctrine.

⸻

Reflection Summary

Deflection thrives on unpreparedness.

⸻

Visual Pairing

Image Concept:
A tennis player volleying back bureaucratic excuses. Caption:
“Return Every Serve.”
